 In John Webster's play <span class="floydstyle em">The White Devil</span>, the poisoned
 character Bracciano hallucinates on his deathbed. After seeing the
 devil, who wears a blue bonnet, breeches, and a great cod-piece "stuck
 full of pins with pearls o'th' head of them," he cries out: "Look you,
 six gray rats that have lost their tails crawl up the pillow; send for
 a rat-catcher." Of the many creepy, weird images in the play, the rats
 on the pillow might be my favorite. The phrase, which also sounds a
 little like the title of a <span class="floydstyle em">giallo</span>, struck me enough to borrow
 here. If Rinaldo manages to fall asleep with the travel pillow on the
 bed the connection to this story is made a little less tenuous.



